      "createdAt": "2026-03-26T00:51:48.678177+00:00",
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, that took courage to share all of that — and I want to make sure you feel heard before we talk about anything else. What you're describing sounds genuinely hard. Poor sleep, no appetite, dreading something you normally care about — that's a lot to carry at once.\n\nI also want to be straight with you, because that's what you deserve: what you're describing — elevated resting HR, disrupted sleep, lost appetite, persistent heavy legs, and dread — those are classic signs that your body is under significant stress. That pattern has a name in exercise physiology, and it matters.\n\n**Can I share what I'm seeing, and why it actually connects to your goal?**\n\nHere's the thing that might feel counterintuitive: pushing through this won't get you to 1:45. It's likely to move you further away from it. When your body is in this state, the training stimulus doesn't land the way it's supposed to — your muscles aren't recovering, your aerobic adaptations aren't consolidating, and the risk of injury climbs. You have 10 weeks. That's actually enough time — *if* you protect the next 7–10 days.\n\nRest right now isn't lost time. It's the work. Your fitness doesn't evaporate in a week; it gets consolidated.\n\nThat said, I want to be honest about my limits here too. The combination of symptoms you're describing — especially the elevated resting HR sustained over a week alongside the appetite and sleep changes — is worth a conversation with a doctor or sports medicine professional, not just a coach. I can adjust your training plan. I can't assess what's happening physiologically inside your body.\n\n**What I'd suggest we do together:**\n\nYou have two real options, and I want you to choose what feels right:\n\n1. **A genuine recovery week** — easy movement only (20–30 min walks or very light jogging at the easy end of your pace range), no structured workouts, sleep as the priority. Then reassess next weekend.\n2. **A modified reduced-load week** — one easy run, one very short easy run, nothing else. Still a significant step back, but with a little more structure if that feels more manageable mentally.\n\nEither way, your 10-week plan has room for this. We'd simply shift the build phase by one week.\n\nWhat's your gut reaction to those two options? And what do you think has been driving the poor sleep — is it training stress, or is life throwing other things at you right now too?"
        }
      ],
